'''Peter Gregory McGehee''' (October 6, 1955 - September 13, 1991) was an [[United States|American]]-born [[Canada|Canadian]] novelist, dramatist and short story writer.

Born in [[Pine Bluff, Arkansas]] to Frank Thomas and Julia Ann May McGehee, Peter moved with his family to Little Rock when he was six. He was the second of three children -- the eldest was Frank Thomas, Jr. and the youngest was Julie. McGehee played the trombone at Parkview High School in Little Rock where he graduated in 1973. McGehee studied at [[Southern Methodist University]] in [[Dallas, Texas|Dallas]] before moving to [[San Francisco]] to work in theatre where he graduated from the University of San Francisco. While living in San Francisco, he wrote his first play, the comedic musical revue ''The Quinlan Sisters''. He also later met Canadian activist [[Douglas Wilson (Canadian gay activist)|Doug Wilson]], who became his partner. The couple moved to [[Saskatoon]] in 1980, and subsequently to [[Toronto]] in 1983. He premiered his second revue, ''The Fabulous Sirs'', and published his first [[novella]], ''Beyond Happiness'', in 1985.

entry.title: Flamenco beach
entry.summary:
←Created page with 'Welcome to Puerto Rico’s most impressive beach by far - and one of the most beautiful beaches of our planet. Playa Flamenco consistently ranks as one of the top b…'

New page

Welcome to Puerto Rico’s most impressive beach by far - and one of the most beautiful beaches of our planet. Playa Flamenco consistently ranks as one of the top beaches in the world and is part of the Blue Flag Beach program.<p>

This gorgeous natural beach has an effect that you can’t put into words - you just have to experience it yourself. Feel the very fine and almost white sand under your feet as you take a walk along the seashore which extends over a length of almost a mile, bathe in the warm crystal clear water or simply submerge into another world and watch the countless colorful fish darting between the corals. But make sure that you always stay alongside the rocks and do not swim above them; otherwise you might hurt yourself as the water level is only minimally higher than the rocks.<p>

Playa Flamenco is one of the must-see places, especially when you live in Puerto Rico, from where Culebra is very easily and cheaply accessible.<p>

One option would be catching the ferry from Fajardo to Culebra, which takes an hour and costs less than $5 for two people. Another possibility are the flights offered daily from San Juan’s Isla Grande Airport (SIG) or from Fajardo. On the island itself you can rent a jeep or simply take the shuttle bus, which runs between the town and Playa Flamenco and cost less than 3 dollars. In addition, there are many private taxis that will take you anyplace you like, like for example to Playa Zoni.<p>

Directly behind the beach there is big camping ground. Here you can also find shower rooms and restrooms. This camp site is the only place on Culebra where camping is permitted. The price per night is $20, which, unfortunately, is not very cheap.<p>
